This paper is likely to belong to the category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it proposes a new method for improving the accuracy and training speed of shapelet-based forest, which is a popular machine learning technique for time series classification. It also introduces a new discriminability metric to identify influential regions for every class, which is a common topic in machine learning research. 

It could also belong to cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) as the paper discusses the concept of discriminative subsequence of time series, which involves discrete mathematics techniques such as pattern matching and combinatorics. 

Additionally, it could be categorized under cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as the proposed method involves constructing a random forest, which is a popular AI technique for classification and regression tasks. 

The paper also mentions the use of shapelets for image classification, which could place it under the category of cs.CV (Computer Vision). 

Finally, the paper discusses the interpretability of the proposed method, which could place it under the category of cs.IR (Information Retrieval) as interpretability is an important topic in information retrieval research.
